<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-843-262  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 843 262.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  August 1990 v9 n8 p32(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple Mac becomes CAD/CAM platform. (includes a related article onUnix, one on rendering, and one on Windows and a brief descriptionof CAD/CAM products for the Macintosh)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Potter, Caren D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The 1990 evaluation of how the Apple Macintosh computer functionsas a platform for professional CAD/CAM shows that the company isdoing its part by producing the Mac IIfx.andP;  The IIfx should competewell against i486-based personal computers and 68030-basedworkstations and should remove the 'too slow for CAD/CAM' stigmaattached to earlier Macintoshes.andP;  The Macintosh does not have thevariety of design and manufacturing applications that areavailable for the IBM compatible personal computers, but the listof software is growing.andP;  The software packages that are available,however, are of good quality, especially Ashlar Vellum, which waswritten for the Macintosh.andP;  Also, a number of third-party boardmanufacturers have announced products based onreduced-instruction-set computing for the Macintosh.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh IIfx (Microcomputer) (usage)Ashlar Vellum (Computer graphics software) (usage).andO;Topic:     Reduced-Instruction-Set ComputersCAD-CAMComputer-Aided ManufacturingUNIX.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>